  <description type="morphology">Culms 11–40 cm, glabrous on angles. Leaves: proximal sheaths brown, fronts with pale brown spots, veinless, with blades, glabrous; leaf blades 3–6 mm wide. Perigynia obovoid.</description>
  <description type="phenology">Fruiting Aug–Sep.</description>
  <description type="habitat">Wet subalpine and alpine meadows;</description>
  <description type="elevation">3000–4500 m;</description>
  <description type="distribution">Colo., Wyo.</description>
  <number>198a.</number>
  <discussion>A common sedge of the southern Rocky Mountains, Carex scopulorum var. scopulorum is distinguished from var. bracteosa by the glabrous stems and sheaths, and by the broader more obovoid perigynia.</discussion>
